{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The distinction between 'prevention' (justice in transfer) and 'correction' (rectification) is subtle and worth an explicit callout. 21% of test-takers chose the tempting distractor (E) 'implementation of a principle of rectification' -- the analysis handles this well but a callout would make the distinction more memorable.", "variant": "comment" }

+{{+**Key Distinction:** The Act was designed to **prevent future fraud** (a transfer issue), not to **correct past injustices** (a rectification issue). This prevention vs. correction distinction is a common LSAT trap in passages about justice and law.+}}

